ce between Wall Street and GAAP. Because of differences in what each group i=
ncluded in their earnings calculations, the results were chaotic. Using GAAP=
, the company lost $9.39 a share. S&P figures it lost $3.19, while the compa=
ny put the loss at 36 cents. Meanwhile, Wall Street says it made 2 cents.=20
