ges taken this year, for example, which is apt to be a lousy one for most co=
mpanies anyway, might include costs that would otherwise have been taken in =
future periods. Prepaying those costs gives a big boost to later earnings. R=
ules for figuring operating earnings would help, but this is an area that wi=
ll always involve a certain amount of judgment--and therefore invite a certa=
in amount of abuse. ``People are going to write off everything they can in t=
he next two quarters because they're having a bad year anyway,'' says Robert=
 G. Atkins, a Mercer Management consultant.=20
